title: Samsung’s Wireless Frame Pro TV Is a Disaster (And I’m Stuck With It)
description: Samsung's new $2,200 Wireless Frame Pro TV is AWFUL! Watch it implode under latency, bugs, and edge‑lit lies. Save on the Rhinoshield AirX at checkout using code "SNAZZYLABS" - https://url.rhinoshield.io/SNAZZYLABS Follow Snazzy Labs on Twitter - https://twitter.com/snazzylabs   Follow me on Bluesky - https://snazzy.fm/UW Follow me on Threads - https://snazzy.fm/XV Follow me on Mastodon - https://snazzy.fm/NN Follow me on Instagram - https://instagram.com/snazzyq  In this Samsung Frame Pro review, I explain why the $2,200 “wireless” TV is a disaster: the Wireless One Connect box causes latency, stutters, and constant disconnects, the micro‑HDMI 2.1 port lacks eARC/ARC for soundbars, Wi‑Fi 7/6GHz interference breaks stability, and HDMI‑CEC mangles Art Mode power behavior. Despite the matte panel and convincing Art Mode, the edge‑lit “Neo QLED powered by mini‑LED” display delivers poor contrast, vertical banding, smeary night scenes, and unhinged default picture settings—with no Dolby Vision. Software is painfully slow (TV Plus bloat), setup is infuriating (mounting/stud issues, cable routing), and even Samsung’s S801D soundbar drops audio over Wi‑Fi, forcing a lower‑quality Bluetooth fallback. If you want a main TV, buy an OLED; for an art TV, cheaper Hisense/TCL models are better. Bottom line: Samsung Frame Pro looks like wall art, but as a wireless TV it’s laggy, unreliable, and wildly overpriced.  0:00 - This is the worst TV I've ever owned 0:29 - What's the point of "Frame"-style TVs? 2:39 - How Is It Wireless? 4:15 - Installation HELL 6:45 - eARC sound bar support is ABYSMAL 8:41 - Wireless TV? Wireless sound bar! (it's bad) 10:28 - WiFi 7 will absolutely jack up this TV 11:30 - Software is laughably bad—I've never used a worse TV 16:15 - Hardware is also bad: Apple TV issues, latency, stutter 18:42 - Samsung literally false advertised mini LED—picture quality stinks 21:27 - But this TV is about ART—so how is it?? 23:22 - "Pro" this TV is not—especially at night 24:04 - Do not buy this TV—it's garbage

title: Best TV of 2025 (Shootout): LG G5 vs Samsung S95F vs Sony BRAVIA 8 II vs Panasonic Z95B
description: Our 2025 TV shootout between the LG G5 & Panasonic Z95B 4-stack WOLED TVs + Samsung S95F & Sony BRAVIA 8 II QD-OLEDs.  All competing TVs were 55 inches in screen size, and were calibrated in SDR and HDR modes to the common standards used within the film and broadcast industry, perceptually matched to a Sony BVM-HX3110 dual-layer LCD mastering monitor capable of reaching a peak brightness of 4000 nits.  All the TVs were masked, so the 6 video professional & sole enthusiast judges didn't know which TV was which when scoring different picture attributes.  00:00 Intro 00:21 Near-black 00:57 Colours 02:12 HDR 03:38 Motion 04:31 Uniformity 05:02 Video processing 05:52 Bright room 06:14 Out of The Box 06:48 Best Home Cinema TV 07:33 Best Living Room TV 11:23 Best TV of 2025 12:37 Shootout format  The judges were (in alphabetical order by surname):  1. Zeb Chadfield, Founder & Chief Vision Officer at The Finish Line 2. Maciej Koper, Professional Calibrator & Reviewer at Wybierz.tv & Choose.tv 3. Ian Lowe, ex-Dolby Vision Post Production 4. James Meredith, Technical Director & Co-Founder at Netvio 5. Julian Nelson, Head of Post Production & Co-Founder at Residence Pictures 6. Luis Pinhao, Imaging Engineer at Cinelab Ltd 7.
